Halve, peel and chop the @red onion{1} into small pieces.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a medium #saucepan{} on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the onion and cook, stirring frequently, until softened, ~{3-4%mins}.

Pour the @water{220%ml} for the bulgur wheat into the saucepan with the onion, 
then stir in the @vegetable stock paste{10%g} and bring to the boil.

Stir in the @bulgur wheat{110%g}, bring back up to the boil and simmer for 
~{1%min}. Pop a #lid{} on the pan and remove from the heat.

Leave to the side for ~{12-15%mins} or until ready to serve.

Meanwhile, peel and grate the @garlic clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Halve the @mangetout{80%g} widthways.

Drain and rinse the @chickpeas{1%400g can} in a #sieve{}.

About 5 mins before the bulgur wheat is ready, heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a 
large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the @king prawns{150%g}, mangetout and a pinch of @chilli flakes{1%pinch}.

> Add less chilli flakes if you'd prefer things milder.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw prawns.

Cook, stirring, until the prawns are almost cooked and the mangetout is tender, 
~{3-4%mins}.

Add the garlic and cook, stirring, until the prawns are cooked, ~{1%min}. 
Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

> IMPORTANT: The prawns are cooked when pink on the outside and opaque in the middle.

Once the bulgur is cooked, fluff up with a #fork{} and stir the chickpeas through.

Stir in the @zhoug style paste{50%g}, then taste and season with salt and pepper.

Share the bulgur between your bowls and top with prawns and mangetout. Enjoy!